#Internal Topology Disclosure 1

##Information:
Vulnerability: Internal Infrastructure Mapping via Public DNS
Status: Completed / Sanitized

Classification: CWE-200 (Information Exposure)

Triage Result: Duplicate / Informative

## Notes:

Sometimes during RECON we sometimes find internal IPs. Companies see this as low-risk and may say "Oh those are internal, they can't be reached externally." To which I say BAH.

I pride myself on thinking like an adversary and to me, discovering internal IPs give us a map of the internal network. Sure you can't do much with the information, but if you are an attacker dead set on exploiting a company, a map let's you skip the discovery phase of a campaign.

Sure, it's post infiltration, but having this map means:

You already know your targets, and what service they provide, so you know exactly where to hit.

Depending on the size of the disclosure, you might be able to map their infrastructure by subnet, by service, or even location.

This allows pinpoint targeted attacks, fuel for SSRF, and general ease of exploitation.

You get to skip one of the LOUDEST parts of exploitation, simply because they couldn't sanatize their DNS profile.


## Synopsis

During reconnaissance, a systemic misconfiguration was identified where numerous public-facing subdomains resolved to RFC 1918 (Private) IP addresses. While frequently dismissed as "Low Risk" due to the non-routable nature of the addresses, this disclosure constitutes a significant intelligence leak. It provides an external actor with a high-fidelity map of the internal network architecture, including the location of critical services like Vault, GHE, and CI/CD pipelines.
